		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="Id71fa1e1682311ea83aee46e6decbb85">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>7:4.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Court appointed experts</headtext>
						<eos/>
						<eop/>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>Under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="USFRER76" w-pub-number="1000607" ID="Id65db10074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Fed. R. Evid. 76</cite.query> and under <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="ES" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-4-706" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id65db10174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. 24-4-706</cite.query>, the court may appoint its own expert witness.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1978110628" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id65e263274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Presnell v. State</ital>
						</cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7880a64074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court said, <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>
						<?page no="182"?>“Common law, statute and rule have recognized the authority of a trial judge in civil and in criminal cases to summon expert witnesses of his own choosing.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I7880cd5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>]</paratext>
					<eos/>
					<eop/>
				</para>
				<para>
					<bop/>
					<bos/>
					<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1985146115" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id661819274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Williams v. Newsome</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7880cd5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court said, <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“[A] trial judge has the inherent power to order a psychiatric examination, but the refusal to do so will not be reversed unless it is shown that the want of an examination would infringe upon the defendant&apos;s right to a fair trial as guaranteed by the Georgia Constitution. <eos/>
						<bos/>This does not mean that the choice of expert rests with the accused.”<eos/>
						<bos/>
						<end.quote refid="QT_0003"/> In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1995148298" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Id6626bf174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">
							<ital>Young v. City of Augusta,</ital>
						</cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="I7880cd5274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>] the Eleventh Circuit held that the district court&apos;s refusal to appoint an expert on psychiatric care to assist indigent former prisoner on motion for summary judgment in civil rights action alleging deliberate indifference to serious medical needs was not error where the presence of genuine issue of fact with respect to deliberate indifference was apparent from the face of record and expert testimony would have been superfluous.<eos/>
					</paratext>
					<eop/>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
		<footnote.block>
			<footnote ID="I7880a64074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>1</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1978110628" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id65e745274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Presnell v. State, 241 Ga. 49, 243 S.E.2d 496 (1978)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d in part</case.history> on other grounds, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1978139540" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Id65e745574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">439 U.S. 14, 99 S. Ct. 235, 58 L. Ed. 2d 207 (1978)</cite.query>
							<?page no="182"?>, followed in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1978132225" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id65e745974d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Griggs v. State, 241 Ga. 317, 245 S.E.2d 269 (1978)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1978133635" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id65ee98274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Westbrook v. State, 242 Ga. 151, 249 S.E.2d 524 (1978)</cite.query>, held that such appointment of an expert was a matter for the discretion of the trial judge.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1982141231" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id65f37a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Jackson v. State, 249 Ga. 751, 295 S.E.2d 53 (1982)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1983111151" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id65f37a574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Wilson v. State, 250 Ga. 630, 300 S.E.2d 640 (1983)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST17-7-130.1" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="Id65f85c074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 17-7-130.1</cite.query>, provides as follows:</paratext>
						<display.quote>
							<para>
								<paratext>
									<begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>At the trial of a criminal case in which the defendant intends to interpose the defense of insanity, evidence may be introduced to prove the defendant&apos;s sanity or insanity at the time at which he is alleged to have committed the offense charged in the indictment or information. <eos/>
									<bos/>When notice of an insanity defense is filed, the court shall appoint at least one psychiatrist or licensed psychologist to examine the defendant and to testify at the trial. <eos/>
									<bos/>This testimony shall follow the presentation of the evidence for the prosecution and for the defense, including testimony of any medical experts employed by the state or by the defense. <eos/>
									<bos/>The medical witnesses appointed by the court may be cross-examined by both the prosecution and the defense, and each side may introduce evidence in rebuttal to the testimony of such a medical witness.<eos/>
									<bos/>
									<end.quote refid="QT_0002"/>
								</paratext>
							</para>
						</display.quote>
						<paratext>Thus this medical witness will be a witness for the court.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7880cd5074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>2</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1978110628" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id660be4274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Presnell v. State, 241 Ga. 49, 56–57, 243 S.E.2d 496 (1978)</cite.query>, <case.history>judgment rev&apos;d in part</case.history> on other grounds, <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1978139540" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000708" ID="Id660be4574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">439 U.S. 14, 99 S. Ct. 235, 58 L. Ed. 2d 207 (1978)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1986108380" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id6610c6274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Thornton v. State, 255 Ga. 434, 339 S.E.2d 240 (1986)</cite.query>, it was error not to appoint a forensic dental expert for the indigent defendant at state expense.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7880cd5174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>3</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1985146115" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Id661a8a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Williams v. Newsome, 254 Ga. 714, 334 S.E.2d 171 (1985)</cite.query>.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
			</footnote>
			<footnote ID="I7880cd5274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">
				<label.designator>4</label.designator>
				<footnote.body>
					<para>
						<bop/>
						<bos/>
						<paratext>
							<cite.query w-src-number="0287017111" w-serial-number="1995148298" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000506" ID="Id662930174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Young v. City of Augusta, Ga. Through DeVaney, 59 F.3d 1160, 32 Fed. R. Serv. 3d 1438 (11th Cir. 1995)</cite.query>
							.<eos/>
						</paratext>
						<eop/>
					</para>
				</footnote.body>
